{"id":"X02782","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"title":"Judge","first_name":"Eliphalet","last_name":"Austin","suffix":"Sr.","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Judge Eliphalet Austin Sr."},"birth":{"year":1761,"county":"Litchfield County","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1838,"month":1,"day":28,"city":"Austinburg","county":"Ashtabula County","state":"Ohio","country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM035","plot_notes":"Austinburg Center Cemetery"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X02783","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1838,"children_ids":["X01418"]}],"education":[],"career":[{"title":"Connecticut Land Company partner","organization":"Connecticut Land Company","dates":"late 1790s","type":"business","notes":"Joined the Connecticut Land Company, formed to settle and develop the section of western Connecticut later called the Connecticut Western Reserve in Ohio. Purchased wide tracts including present-day Austinburg Township, which bears his name."},{"title":"Founder","organization":"Austinburg Township, Ashtabula County, Ohio","dates":"1799","type":"civic","notes":"Settled at present-day Austinburg in 1799. The township is named for him. Responsible for carrying the mail in the region; operated a cattle-dealing operation."},{"title":"State Senator","organization":"Ohio State Senate","dates":"1829-1831","type":"politics"}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM102","role":"resident_owner","notes":"Built the Eliphalet Austin House Austinburg OH 1815 (per Wikipedia; 1811 per local tradition). NRHP listed 1975. Heavily modified Italianate style by his grandson Louis B. Austin in the 1860s."}],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["town_founder","ohio_migration","senator"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"civic_peer","related_id":"H00443","display_label":"Co-founders of Austinburg church and Western Reserve College","link_text":"Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Founder of Austinburg Township, Ohio Western Reserve","body":"A Connecticut Land Company partner, Eliphalet purchased wide tracts across the Connecticut Western Reserve in the late 1790s and settled at present-day Austinburg in 1799 — the township still bears his name. He carried the mail across the region, operated a cattle-dealing business, and served in the Ohio Senate 1829-1831."},{"number":2,"category":"religion","header":"His wife rode horseback to recruit a minister","body":"In spring 1810, his wife Sybil Dudley Austin rode six hundred miles by horseback to Bristol Connecticut — alone, with her wardrobe in a portmanteau — to recruit Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles to settle Ashtabula County's first Congregational minister. Giles, his wife Sally, and their eight children arrived in Austinburg the following summer 1811. The Austin-Cowles partnership defined Austinburg's pioneer era."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"His Austinburg house is on the National Register","body":"Eliphalet built the brick house at 1879 State Route 45 Austinburg in 1811 (or 1815 per Wikipedia). His grandson Louis B. Austin remodelled it in the Italianate style during the 1860s."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Wikipedia: Eliphalet Austin House","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eliphalet_Austin_House","accessed":"2026-05"},{"short":"Williams Brothers 'History of Ashtabula County' (1878), biography of Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles (re: Mrs. Austin's recruitment ride)","url":"https://ohiogenealogyexpress.com/ashtabula/ashtaco_1878_bios/ashtaco_1878_bios_cowlesGiles.html","accessed":"2026-05"},{"short":"National Register of Historic Places, NRHP reference No. 75001313","accessed":"2026-05"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"eliphalet-austin-sr-1761"},"X02783":{"id":"X02783","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"first_name":"Sybil","last_name":"Austin","maiden_name":"Dudley","married_names":["Austin"],"extra_names":"Also recorded as 'Sibyl Dudley' (per EH); 'Sibbell' (per WikiTree variant)","gender":"female","display_name":"Sybil Dudley Austin"},"birth":{"year":1761,"city":"Conway","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1844,"month":4,"day":2,"city":"Austinburg","county":"Ashtabula County","state":"Ohio","country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM035","plot_notes":"Austinburg Center Cemetery — buried with husband Eliphalet"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_name":"Daniel Dudley (Daniel, Caleb, Joseph, William Dudley line) — William Dudley b. Richmond/Sheen Surrey England, came to Guilford CT 1636"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X02782","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_husband","end_year":1838,"children_ids":["X01418"]}],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["ohio_migration"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_orbit","related_id":"H00443","display_label":"Recruited the Connecticut minister who founded Austinburg's church","link_text":"Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Rode 600 miles alone to recruit a minister","body":"In spring 1810 Sybil concluded that the new settlement of Austinburg needed a settled Congregational minister. She rode alone by horseback over six hundred miles to Bristol Connecticut — clothing in a portmanteau, thirty-day journey through unsettled forest — to persuade Sally and Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles to migrate to the Western Reserve. Her ride succeeded; the Cowles family arrived in Austinburg in 1811."},{"number":2,"category":"education","header":"Daughters all attended Litchfield Female Academy","body":"Four of her daughters attended the Litchfield Female Academy — Sybil Webb in 1818, Chloe, Florilla, and Sophia. The Academy founded by Sarah Pierce in 1792 was among the earliest formal secondary schools for women in the United States."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Williams Brothers 'History of Ashtabula County' (1878), biography of Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles","url":"https://ohiogenealogyexpress.com/ashtabula/ashtaco_1878_bios/ashtaco_1878_bios_cowlesGiles.html","accessed":"2026-05"},{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909, entry #688 (re: marriage of Rev. Eliphalet Austin Jr to Sally Berrien Cowles, identifies mother as Sibyl Dudley)","url":"https://archive.org/details/descendantsofrev00hook","accessed":"2026-05"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"sybil-dudley-1761"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM035","name":"Austinburg Center Cemetery","city":"Austinburg","county":"Ashtabula County","state":"Ohio","country":"United States","gps":{"latitude":41.7533,"longitude":-80.8533},"visitable":true,"notes":"Cemetery of the Congregational church founded by Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles. Contains graves of Rev. Cowles, his wife Sallie White Cowles, and son Edward Giles Hooker Cowles.","hooker_connections":["H00443","H01142","H01143","H01144","H01145","H01146","H01147","H01148","H01149","HD3713","HD3714","HD3715","HD3716","X00259","X01418","X02782","X02783","HD3718","I00397","HD3717"]},"institutionsById":{"INST044":{"id":"INST044","primary_name":"Case Western Reserve University","name":"Case Western Reserve University","short_name":"Case Western Reserve","alt_names":["Western Reserve College (1826)"],"type":"university","founding_year":1826,"location":{"city":"Cleveland","state":"Ohio","country":"United States"},"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Case_Western_Reserve_University","primary_persons":["H00443"],"hooker_connected_people":["H00443","H01149","I00495"],"person_ids":["X01418","X01997"],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"notes":"Founded 1826 in Hudson, Summit County, Ohio as Western Reserve College by a group of Connecticut Congregationalist settlers, with Rev. Giles Hooker Cowles (H00443) among its founders. Called 'the Yale of the West' — same motto (Lux et Veritas), same entrance standards, same curriculum as Yale. First college in northern Ohio. H00443 (Giles Hooker Cowles, gen 5 Hooker descendant) was named 'Hooker' for both his grandfather Giles Hooker and the Hooker ancestral line. He graduated Yale 1789, moved to Austinburg, Ashtabula County OH as a missionary (Ohio Home Missionary Society), and was instrumental in establishing the college infrastructure of the Western Reserve. First college west of the Appalachians to enroll (1832) and graduate (1836) an African-American student. Hudson was a major Underground Railroad stop. Co-founder Owen Brown was the father of abolitionist John Brown. The Newton family (HD2925 John Newton, HD2927 Eben Newton) and Elisha Whittlesey (X01997) all operated in the Western Reserve contemporaneously. Whittlesey was public prosecutor for the entire Western Reserve from 1806; Eben Newton was a judge and state senator. Moved to Cleveland 1882, merged with Case Institute of Technology 1967. H00443 is the brother of H00442 (Pamelia Cowles Thompson), whose granddaughter Laura Hooker Thompson Newton (HD0532) married John Newton (HD2925) — making the founding of Western Reserve College a family affair in the deepest sense. Among the original 12-member founding board of three presbyteries that met at Warren OH 1825 to choose a college site (selecting Hudson, now Summit County): from Grand River Presbytery, Rev. Dr. Giles Hooker Cowles (H00443) and Rev. Eliphalet Austin (X01418, with Harvey Coe and A. Griswold); from Portage Presbytery, Rev. Joseph Treat, John Steward, J. H. Whittlesey, Lemuel Porter; from Huron Presbytery, A. H. Betts, L. B. Sullivan, Hon. Samuel Cowles (of San Francisco — his namesake nephew HD3710 was 2 years old in 1825), D. Betts. Charter obtained 1826."}},"crossConnections":[]}